            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Lin Wong is a daughter of the Richmond District, born and raised in the foggy avenues of San Francisco. Her parents, immigrants from Guangdong, ran a small laundromat on Geary Boulevard, where the scent of steam and detergent defined her childhood. The eldest of three, Mei-Lin was responsible and pragmatic from a young age, translating for her parents and helping with the family business after school. She graduated from George Washington High School with a quiet dream of becoming a graphic artist, her sketchbooks filled with portraits of the diverse faces she saw on the bus every day.\n\nHer path veered sharply when her mother suffered a debilitating stroke shortly after Mei-Lin\u2019s graduation. College was no longer an option. Instead, she took on the role of primary caregiver, a duty she accepted with a stoicism that masked her own deferred hopes. This experience led her to get certified as a home health aide. What began as a necessity born from family crisis evolved into a genuine calling. For over two decades, she has dedicated herself to caring for the city\u2019s elderly, offering not just physical assistance but compassionate companionship.\n\nNow 45, Mei-Lin\u2019s life is a tapestry of routine and quiet purpose. Her day begins at 5:30 AM in the same rent-controlled apartment she grew up in. She takes the 38R Geary bus across town to her current client, an elderly gentleman in Pacific Heights. She doesn't just administer medication and prepare meals; she listens to his stories of an older San Francisco, finding a profound connection in their shared history of the city. Her own social life is small but deep, revolving around a weekly dim sum with her younger brother and occasional phone calls with a few trusted colleagues.\n\nMei-Lin doesn't dream of riches, but of simple security. Her biggest aspiration is to save enough to take a trip to her parents\u2019 ancestral village in China, to see the world they left behind. In quiet moments, she still pulls out a sketchbook, drawing the gentle, lined face of her client or the view of the Golden Gate Bridge from his window. Her connection to San Francisco is etched not in tech booms or trendy restaurants, but in the steadfast rhythm of her commute and the invisible, vital support she provides to its most vulnerable residents."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being twelve, the air thick with steam at the family laundromat. A frustrated customer was yelling, and her father\u2019s English failed him. Mei-Lin stepped forward, her small hands still red from folding hot sheets, and translated perfectly. In that moment, she felt the weight of her family\u2019s world settle on her shoulders. It wasn't a burden, but a purpose. The quiet pride in her father\u2019s eyes taught her that responsibility was its own form of love, a lesson that would define her entire life.\n\n2.\nThe hospital air smelled sterile, a harsh contrast to the laundromat's familiar scent. She was eighteen, her art school pamphlets still on her desk. Seeing her mother diminished in the bed, unable to speak, a silent pact was made. She looked at her father\u2019s terrified face and knew. Her sketchbook felt a million miles away. There was no choice, only duty. It was the day she packed away one dream to embrace another, a future of quiet, necessary care that chose her.\n\n3.\nHer first long-term client, a stern woman in the Sunset, hadn't spoken more than a few words in weeks. One foggy afternoon, Mei-Lin was sketching the view when the woman whispered, \u201cThe foghorns used to sound sadder.\u201d Suddenly, they were sharing stories of the old city, a bridge of memory built between them. It was then Mei-Lin understood her work wasn't just about bodies, but about safeguarding the stories they held. Her purpose clicked powerfully into place, transforming duty into a calling.\n\n4.\nJust last year, her current client, Mr. Rossi, was napping in his armchair, sunlight catching the fine lines around his eyes. She quietly took out her sketchbook and began to draw. The diverse faces she\u2019d once sought on the 38 Geary were all contained in this one. She wasn\u2019t capturing a stranger, but a life she knew intimately. It was a moment of quiet revelation: her art and her caregiving were not two different paths, but one, intertwined expression of seeing people.\n\n5.\nEvery Sunday, the clatter of porcelain and the steam from bamboo baskets at the dim sum parlor feels like home. Her younger brother complains about his tech job, and she listens, pushing a shrimp dumpling his way. They slip between Cantonese and English, the language of their shared history. In this simple, weekly ritual, she feels the unwavering bedrock of family. It\u2019s a quiet tether to her past and the most profound security she knows, more valuable than any stock option or savings account."
